{"title_page": "Cliff Wilson", "text_new": "{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://www.cuetracker.net/Players/Cliff-Wilson/Career-Total-Statistics\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\bcuetracker\\.net\\b</code> on the local blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=false}}\n{{short description|Welsh professional snooker player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{more citations needed|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n|name         = Cliff Wilson\n|image        = Cliff Wilson.jpg\n|caption      = \n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1934|5|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Tredegar, Wales|Tredegar]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]]\n|death_date    = {{death date|1994|5|21|df=y}} (aged 60)\n|death_place   = \n| Sport country = {{WAL}}\n| Nickname     = \n| Professional = 1979\u20131994\n| High ranking = 16 ([[Snooker world rankings 1988/1989|1988\u201389]])\n| Current rank = \n| Prize money  = \u00a3241,965<ref name=\"cuetracker.net\">http://www.cuetracker.net/Players/Cliff-Wilson/Career-Total-Statistics</ref>\n| High break   = 136 ([[1989 Grand Prix (snooker)|1989 Grand Prix]])<ref name=\"cuetracker.net\">http://www.cuetracker.net/Players/Cliff-Wilson/Career-Total-Statistics</ref>\n| Century break = 6<ref name=\"cuetracker.net\">http://www.cuetracker.net/Players/Cliff-Wilson/Career-Total-Statistics</ref>\n| Best finish  = Quarter-final <small>(5 times)</small>\n| Other wins = 1\n}}\n'''Cliff Wilson''' (10 May 1934{{spaced ndash}}21 May 1994<ref name=\"Indy Obit\" />) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] professional [[snooker]] player. He became 1978 World Amateur Champion. After turning professional he got into the world's top 16 in 1988 at the age of 54, despite very poor eyesight and a number of other ailments.\n\n== Amateur years ==\nWilson was a talented amateur snooker player who grew up in the same town, [[Tredegar, Wales|Tredegar]], as his friend and snooker rival [[Ray Reardon]].<ref name=\"GOBIT\">{{cite news |last=Everton |first=Clive |date=28 May 1994|title=Cue for a happy life |work=The Guardian |page=30|via=ProQuest Historical Newspapers: The Guardian and The Observer. Retrieved 28 September 2019.}}</ref> He won the British Under-19 Championship in 1952 and 1953<ref name=\"SOBIT\">{{cite magazine |last=Everton |first=Clive  |title=Obituary. Cliff Wilson: a great snooker character |magazine=Snooker Scene |pages=11\u201312 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=June 1994 }}</ref> and the Welsh Amateur Championship in 1956.<ref name=\"WBSA\">{{cite web |url=https://www.welshsnooker.com/welsh-championship-records |title=Welsh Championship Records |publisher=Welsh Snooker (WBSA) |website=welshsnooker.com |access-date=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Giving up the game ==\nSnooker's popularity was on the wane during the 1950s and it was extremely difficult to join the small, closed professional circuit. Wilson became disillusioned with the game and gave up snooker completely for fifteen years. During this time he worked at the steelworks at [[Llanwern]].<ref name=\"Indy Obit\">{{cite news|last=Hodgson|first=Guy|title=Obituary: Cliff Wilson|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-cliff-wilson-1438835.html|accessdate=2013-01-16|newspaper=The Independent|date=27 May 1994}}</ref>\n\n== Turning professional ==\nWilson's interest in the game rekindled in the early 1970s and, after winning the [[IBSF World Snooker Championship|IBSF World Amateur Championship]] in 1978, he finally turned professional the following year at the age of 45.<ref name=\"Indy Obit\" /> He broke into the top sixteen for one season, 1988/89, a remarkable achievement for someone aged 55. \n\nHe later went on to win the first World Seniors Championship in 1991 (beating Eddie Charlton 5\u20134 in the final), at the time picking up a cheque for \u00a316,000, his highest prize winnings.<ref name=\"SEN\">{{cite magazine |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=How Cliff Wilson became king of the golden oldies  |magazine=Snooker Scene |pages=17\u201319 |publisher=Everton's News Agency |issue=November 1991}}</ref>\n\nHis popular exhibition matches were advertised with the phrase \"You've never seen anything like it!\"<ref name=\"FARCE\">{{cite book |last=Everton |first=Clive |date=2012 |title=Black Farce and Cue Ball Wizards = |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |pages=372 |isbn=978-1780575681  }}</ref>\n\nHe was known as a fast player and a dangerous potter; but, although he played in the World Championship at the [[Crucible Theatre]] on eight occasions, he never progressed beyond the first round \u2013 a record he shares with [[Rex Williams]].\n\nHe played a young [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the 1992 [[UK Championship (snooker)|UK championship]], winning 9\u20138<ref name=\"Indy Obit\" /> against the then 16-year-old who won the championship the following year.<ref name=\"TOBIT\">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Obituary: Cliff Wilson |work=The Times (London) |page=19 |date=24 May 1994 |via=The Times Digital Archive. Retrieved 24 November 2019.}} </ref>\n\nThe highest break of his career was 136 at the [[1989 Grand Prix (snooker)|1989 Grand Prix]].\n\n==Illness and death==\nTowards the end of his life, Wilson suffered from a number of problems with his back, knee and heart, eventually developing an 'inoperable disease of the liver and pancreas'. Although he continued to play professionally, recording a [[century break]] in the 1994 International Open in January 1994, he succumbed in May of that year, aged 60.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/WilsonC.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-03-31 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331002654/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Players/WilsonC.html |archivedate=31 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'